<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> 10 Year History of SWCCG, Part I<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2864'>Brandon "Jabba_the_Ruck" Ruck</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2864&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 19, 2006</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Welcome all SWCCG players and fans. It is time for a history lesson. Through my years of playing SWCCG, I have noticed many things that have changed since Premiere hit the shelves back in December of 1995. In my growing efforts to educate those about the game through my articles, I have decided to create yet another article that can be used as a tool for those interested in the history of the game. This article will go through the entire history of the game. My goal here is to collect and store all important information about the game, and where it has come from. I wanted to create an article that a player could go to when he or she wanted to recall what the game was like in the earlier years. <br />
<br />
Many of you have been playing since the very beginning, and remember how very simple the game was back then. In this article, I have organized all the dates that the product was released. So finally we have one place that someone can go to do find out when a specifc set came out. Also, I decided to post the World Champion decks for both sides that were used to win the World title for that year. The first Worlds was in 1996, and took place at a time when only Premiere and A New Hope were out to play with. Since then, year after year, a new set has changed the way the game was played. I hope this article can give everyone a clear understanding of how very big and complex the game has become in its 10 years of existence. <br />
<br />
Because I had to go through 10 years, I broke it up into two parts so that I could go ahead and release the part that I had finished. I also wanted it to be easy for someone to use. So a two part history just seemed like a better idea. Part 1 goes from Creation in 1995 to the end of 2000 with Part 2 picking up in 2001 to current V sets. Also please forgive any grammer or mispelled words. Its hard to find all them mistake in an article this long.  If it seems like the layout for each decklist is different, it&#39;s because some were copy and pasted from Decipher&#39;s old website.<br />
<br />
To save space, I have replaced the following:<br />
<br />
Light Side = LS<br />
Dark Side = DS<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
10 Year History of SWCCG, Part I<br />
<br />
<br />
Chapter 1:        In the Beginning<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
In December of 1995, right before Christmas, the Premiere set of 324 cards was released. The set was composed of cards taken from the original A New Hope movie providing players with their first version of Darth Vader, Luke Skywalker, Obi-Wan Kenobi, Leia Organa, Han Solo, and C-3P0. The idea behind this set was to introduce the game as well as it could without being too complicated. By itself, Premiere was extremely basic and did require more cards to be truly effective. That is why in February of 1996, Decipher released a Two-player Introduction set as a tool to teach players how to play the game before a player spent a lot of money on the main set. The two player set included six unique cards that included a very weak version of Vader and Luke, which were created to be previews to the game, and were not truly playable in any deck. <br />
<br />
At this very early time, the game was so basic with only a few choices for sites and starships. The majority of games took place on the ground, and consisted of players activating, then saving force or immediately drawing up to find more sites to deploy. Once the DS got Darth Vader out, and the LS got Obi-Wan Kenobi out, the rest of the game was compiled of huge Sense/Alter wars until one side was left with no more Jedi powers. Jedi powers were so important to your deck, that literally 1/3 of it was just Senses and Alters. Usually, the war took place when the DS tried to play A Circle is Now Complete to immediately place the strongest LS character out of play. Of course, back then, the out of play rule had not been clarified, so many just believed that just that copy of Obi was out of play and another one could be played later in the game. Once the side had lost the S/A war, the rest of the game was draining or setting up a beatdown with Ellis Helrod / Nabrun Leids to move characters all around the table. To follow this first set in April of 1996, was the Jedi Pack with 11 unique cards, most of which had no game text. In that same month, Decipher released the two Rebel leader ships; Red Leader in Red 1 and Gold Leader in Gold 1. Both the Jedi Packs and Leader ships were not sold in stores. They were given out at demos and tournaments to players as they learned to play the game.  <br />
<br />
As the months went by, the game got a huge boost in July of 1996 with the introduction of the A New Hope set of 162 cards. The set included all the rest of the cards from the first movie that were not in the Premiere set. The first versions of Chewbacca and R2-D2 were introduced, as well as, the first Death Star, which immediately became the most popular starting location for DS. Although it allowed the LS to go first, the three Force it provided gave the DS an early advantage in setting up their game. The only thing the LS had going for them at the time was Tantive IV, which allowed for direct deployment to the Death Star. Combined with the Millennium Falcon, and the Rebel Leaders, the LS had the advantage in space over the DS ships that had no immunity to attrition. Only Vader’s Custom TIE could provide a force in space with immunity <4, and rarely got out with Darth Vader usually already deployed on the ground. A New Hope introduced many very popular uncommons and commons; Monnok / Grimtaash, Ghhhk / Houjix, and Undercover, which are still used today. <br />
<br />
After a few months of the two sets, Decipher decided to create their major tournament scene, and hosted its very first Worlds Tournament in November 1996. Below is the two decks that the very first SWCCG World Champion Raphael Asselin used to win. You will notice how very basic they are in comparison to the decks played today. There were no objectives, starting interrupts, or ANY card that can download anything. These decks both relied on getting what you needed through simply drawing the cards in your force pile. If you notice, both decks have a lot of Senses & Alters. His strategy for LS was to use How Did We Get Out of This Mess? to find all the cards he needed quickly, while the DS deck was built as a space deck, with Vader going where he was needed.  You might also notice that both his decks don’t play with Traffic Control or Reactor Terminal. Two cards that were standard to almost every deck built in the early years of the game. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
