<br />
<br />
<br />
Chapter 2:        The Game Continues<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
In Novemeber of 1996, the next 162 card set in line, Hoth, was released. It was not legal for the Worlds Tournament that same month. Hoth introduced a whole new planet for the game to play on. This set began the division of the movies as each set from here on out would introduce cards from that part of the movie. Hoth, of course, provided the game with all the scenes from the beginning scene of the Empire Strikes Back. This set finally gave some more options for ground with the introduction of Walkers and General Veers for DS, as well as, Anakin’s Lightsaber, and the all powerful Hoth Shields with Echo Base Occupation for LS. Many decks would be built around this protective strategy as the DS could not deploy to any site protected by the Shields. They were forced to deploy on the outermost marker and then move in. This allowed the LS to defend against the characters that may have been deployed to invade the planet. <br />
<br />
The set introduced Commander Luke, who was an evolved version of the original. Although more powerful, was the first of many characters Decipher decided would have “deployment restrictions,” which required that the character be deployed to only a specific planet in order to be played. This type of deployment would last through all of the sets introduced from the Empire Strikes Back. <br />
<br />
A few months later in March of 1997, Decipher introduced an updated Two-Player Introduction Set based around Hoth. Like the first Two-Player box, this set had seven unique cards that you could only obtain from this box set. Two of which were Walker Garrison and the Imperial Walker. Walker Garrison was the first big drain strategy introduced to the game. It literally gave the DS a way to drain for 10 or more cards in a single turn. The demand on these unique cards drove the value of this second box set way up to where it was almost impossible to find in stores. <br />
<br />
Although Hoth provided many strong cards to the game, it didn’t change the game all that much. Then, shortly after the Hoth Two-player set came out, the next set in line, Dagobah, was released in April of 1997. Dagobah provided the middle of the Empire Strikes Back by including all the Dagobah locations, Asteroids, and Bounty Hunters seen in the movie, as well as introducing a new Jedi power, Control. This set is known to be the sole introduction of some of the cheesiest strategies the game has ever and will ever see. In this one set, players had the ability to win games with almost no interaction with the opponent. The LS got the majority of help with Jedi Training through Yoda and Son of Skwalker. The first Jedi Test, Great Warrior, took away all force drain bonuses from the DS. Anger, Fear, and Aggression could be ‘inserted’ into the DS deck to cause four cards in damage for them not initiating a Battle. Dagobah was the first location that could pull sites directly from the reserve deck. Once on table, all Dagobah locations were completely protected from any DS foe as Dagobah deployment rules restricted ANY deployment unless the card itself allowed it to be deployed there. The DS had to literally load up a ship and land on the planet in order to stop the LS party. If all of that wasn’t enough, the LS player could play Revolution on Yoda’s Hut and add Lightsaber Proficiency to Son of Skywalker whose text allowed you to find his lightsaber. All of this would give you a solid drain of 4, while playing On the Edge to retrieve any cards that the Darkside might have caused. Keep in mind that there was no such thing as a ‘Battleground’ or cards that cancelled drains (except Control), so the Dagobah drain stayed there all game. <br />
<br />
Although the ‘Dagobah’ based deck was almost unbeatable. It could be beat with the other really cheesy strategy known to all as Odds. The Odds strategy involved simply deploying any three characters to the table, and then ‘Inserting’ an Effect; (3720 to 1 / Never Tell Me the Odds) into your opponents deck. When this Effect reached the top through activating and drawing destiny, each player would count up the destiny number of the 3 lowest characters on table. The lowest total lost that much Force in difference. So, if I had Vader, Tarkin, and Ozzel on table, then I had a total of 2, while the LS who inserted the Odds card would have 5 from R2, 5 from Wioslea and 4 from a random droid. So the DS would have to lose 12 cards!! The bad thing about this lame strategy is it stayed in existence for three years before it was finally stopped by cards made in Death Star 2, which wasn’t released until 2000.    <br />
<br />
Of course, if both of those strategies weren’t enough for one set. Decipher also thought it would be cool to include the Asteroids, which for the most part were not a bad strategy. If only the original Asteroid Sanctuary wasn’t made to cause direct damage during OPPONENTS control phase. So you would be draining during your turn, and then making them lose force during their turn, after you dropped 1 to 3 of them on the previous turn. It was a totally broken strategy and was immediately errataed to be during the LS’s control phase. <br />
<br />
Shortly after Dagobah was released in April, Decipher decided to release another supplement product, the First Anthology, in May of 1997. The First Anthology was the first product to preview cards from sets that were awhile from being released. This one included five cards from Special Edition; Boba Fett, Commander Wedge Antilles, Jabba’s Influence, X-Wing Assualt Squadron, and the Death Star Assault Squadron. They were all produced in white bordered to show they were the preview version of the card. By purchasing the Anthology, a player would also receive 2x Unlimited Premiere starter decks, 2x A New Hope packs, and 2x Hoth packs, as well as, a nice box to store your decks.    <br />
<br />
With the creation of Dagobah, the game took a big turn in a different direction. You would have thought that Decipher would have noticed the problems that Dagobah created for the game and immediately fix them, but they didn’t. The following set, Cloud City, was released in Novemeber of 1997 to complete the sets from the Empire Strikes Back. It finally gave the players their first version of Lando Calrissian and Boba Fett, as well as, introducing new versions of main characters with Princess Leia and Captain Han Solo. This new version of Han is still considered to be the best choice for a Han to pilot the Falcon. Although the set did add to the game with new locations and powerful Interrupts and Effects in You Are Beaten / Clash of Sabers, Imperial Decree, Path of Least Resistance, Smoke Screen, It’s a Trap, Dark Deal, and Epic Duel. At the time, Epic Duel was not very easy to play because you had no way of finding anything and could still lose the game even with both Obi and Luke out of play. Imperial Decree allowing for Force Drain bonuses and Revolution to be cancelled was really the only card that the DS could use to counter the Dagobah deck. The set also didn’t include a direct way to cancel Odds. <br />
<br />
You would think that the set couldn’t have made the Dagobah deck any better. Instead, it created an even powerful strategy by introducing Clouds, which could be deployed to the Dagaboh system to allow for an additional drain of 6 once a Tibana Gas Miner was deployed to the planet with Great Warrior. So even if the Hut was Revolved back and no bonus drains were allowed, the LS player could still drain for three in the Clouds with almost nothing the DS player could do. By far, the most powerful card in that set was Dark Deal. This card provided the DS with their own bonus drain effect to match the LS having EBO to play since Hoth. Much like EBO, Dark Deal require the DS player to place a number of characters and even a TIE out in or to deploy the card. The LS had to occupy a number of locations just like EBO in order to cancel the Effect that was immune to alter.    <br />
<br />
This time the new set was released in time for the 1997 Worlds, and many players found themselves playing against fresh decks with cards that had only been out a few weeks. You will notice that in just one year, the two World Champion decks have a totally different feel to them. Phillip Jacobs played two decks that took a defensive side to playing as he reacted to what his opponent was doing. If you notice that his Dark deck sports THE most popular ships that were included in every DS deck because they were the only ships that had immunity. You will still notice that both decks had completely no way to find any Effect, Interrupt, or most importantly a site. The game still began much slower with both players using their first few turns to simply set up their sites and find some characters. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
