<br />
<br />
Chapter 3:        A Change is Coming<br />
<br />
<br />
With the second Worlds Tournament in the books, Decipher continued their path to release new sets. In April of 1998, Jabba’s Palace began the division of sets that would be released for the Return of the Jedi. Like Cloud City, the set was also 180 cards and is still the largest set of characters with 93. Literally every character that could be seen in or around Jabba’s Palace was included in the set. Jabba the Hutt lead the charge for the DS characters while the LS got a new versions of Artoo, Lando, and Leia. Although Princess Leia Organa was not very popular and saw almost no playing time in decks. The creation of Jabba’s Palace would introduce a new card type, the Starting Interrupt (Twi’lek Advisor DS/ The Signal LS), which for the first time allowed a player to start the game with any Effect that deployed for free. The Jabba’s Palace site provided the DS with a location that could deploy related sites from the Reserve Deck. Combined with Expand the Empire being started on the site, the DS could literally deploy every single related Jabba’s Palace site on the first turn if the game. This set up gave the DS 9 Force after their first turn, a strategy totally unheard of until this set. It also could remove the majority of floating 0s that a normal deck would have had in the past. <br />
<br />
Because the set had no version of Luke, Decipher created I Must Be Allowed to Speak, which allowed the Son of Skywalker version of Luke to deploy to Tatooine overriding his game text restricting deployment to only Dagobah and Cloud City. In this set, Decipher decided to finally create a card (Torture DS / Don’t Forget the Droids LS) that could cancel the Odds mess from Dagobah. The only problem was that it was still an Interrupt, so you had to be lucky enough to have one in your hand by the time the Odds Effect popped. The other problem was that a player playing Odds would usually just play it in many copies so that after the average player used both of their Odds Interrupts to cancel it. The Odds player would grab it, and then resume the very cheesy strategy of non interaction card lose. <br />
<br />
With the success of Jabba’s Palace in place, Decipher decided to expand on the very weak Sealed Deck Tournament Format. Until this time, the entire format of Sealed Deck was trapped in a world of total luck. The ability of the player to win consistently playing in this format until now was totally unheard of. To fix this problem, Decipher released the Official Tournament Sealed Deck in May of 1998. They consisted of six different collectable boxes with different characters (Vader, Luke, Leia, Boba Fett, C-3P0, and Jabba) that players continue to use at tournaments to hold their decks. In the boxes, every player would get the same 18 OTSD Premium cards (9 dark & 9 light) that were designed specifically for Sealed deck games to help level eliminate the luck factor. The 9 cards that a player could obtain would add the missing strategy that a normal game of Sealed Deck was lacking. <br />
<br />
Finally, SWCCG had become a solid CCG with 6 complete sets. It was time for Decipher to release their Second Anthology in July of 1998 that would preview 6 more cards the same way the First Anthology did just one year prior. This time the Second Anthology came with a gold box, which included two packs of Dagobah and Cloud City, as well as, 8 packs of Unlimited Premiere. Up until now, both Anthology’s preview cards had still not been released in their main set. Fans began to prepare for another large set to equal the size of the first Premiere set.  <br />
<br />
As with Hoth and Cloud City, the 7th SWCCG set, Special Edition, was released in Novemeber of 1998. It came just in time for Worlds that year, so players had the same experience from the previous year playing against decks that were completely new. The new set would introduce 324 new cards, as well as, a totally new rule book included in all new pre-packed Sealed Decks for each side. The Sealed Deck each came with 20 fixed cards each made for that specific side. This set would introduce Darth Vader, Dark Lord of the Sith and Ben Kenobi, which provided players with an option to which type of powerful character they wanted to have in their deck. The release of DLOTS would greatly help the game by giving more players an opportunity to obtain a version of Vader with the original Darth Vader at that time reaching costs of $70+. <br />
<br />
Special Edition brought about the largest change to the game up to this point by introducing a totally new type of deck type called Objectives. Each side got 5 different Objectives that would allow the player to play a deck that had a specific purpose other than simply finding ways to either drain or cause damage. They sped the game up by giving the players a totally new feel to playing the game. No longer was a game of SWCCG restricted to drains, deploying, and battling. By completing the requirements of the 0 side of the Objective, the card would flip to the 7 side, which would give the player an advantage over the opponent. So much so that many times the opponent would be required to flip the Objective back to the 0 side in order to have a chance of winning the game. Of course not every Objective that was flipped provided total victory for the player, some of them simply made it more difficult for the opponent to obtain to win with their original strategy. <br />
<br />
Decipher thought this set would continue the pace of the game as it was currently the second most popular CCG behind Magic. The problem this set created was it introduced a very very bad strategy through one of the Objectives. Imperial Occupation DS / Local Uprising LS aka Operatives took over the game like a bad virus. The Objective was so overly powerful that literally no other strategy could easily beat it. No matter what your hand or strategy was, it would have no chance against this Objective. The set was released right before Worlds, so only the players that played this strategy had any chance of winning. The 1998 Worlds Tournament was a total mess. No longer was it a test of who the best players were, but only who was smart enough to play this type of Operative. Day 3 of Worlds literally had only one deck that wasn’t Operatives. Looking at the two decks, you will not see anything that even looks like a SWCCG strategy, past or present. They are included as a reminder of the mistakes that were made in this game.    <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
