<br />
<br />
Chapter 4:	Where are the Sets?<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
With the 3rd Worlds Tournament in the books, Decipher released a new concept card to the game at the end of 1998 known as the Enhanced Premiere Pack or EPP. Each had a special card that was sold in a special pack that showed the card on the outside and included 4 packs of unlimited Premiere. The special cards consisted of 6 versions of main characters that all had a Permanent Weapon built into their game text. Vader, Luke, and Obi all had their lightsabers, while Fett, Han, and Leia all had a blaster. To make up for a blaster being a weaker weapon, the three of them all got an added text for adding a battle destiny if with a specific character(s). These destiny adding characters were the first of their kind and proved to be very popular throughout the game for years to come. <br />
<br />
As 1999 went by, Decipher continued to push back the release of the next set, Endor. In the past, the new set had always come out in April. This time it was released in June. Players were excited to find yet another new planet of possibilities as well as two new Objectives to play with. Both were based around the Endor: Bunker and involved either keeping it safe or blowing it up. Although the idea was different, neither Objective proved to be all that powerful and was usually only used as a platform for a mains and toys deck. <br />
As for the rest of the set, the LS gained the all popular Ewoks as well as a General version of Han and a Skywalker version of Leia. The DS received no main characters but did gain many unique AT-STs, as well as, a new AT-AT to play with in Tempest 1. Endor as a whole was not very popular as far as total cards to play with. It did however include some very popular LS characters (General Crix Madine) and red cards ( Strike Planning, I Know, Lost in the Wilderness / Always Thinking with Your Stomach, and Insurrection / Imperial Arrest Order). <br />
<br />
Endor was the first to introduce the SWCCG world to Foils. The Endor Foils were a small set of mainly the rarest cards in the set; General Solo, Daughter of Skywalker, Tempest 1 etc. They were the first set that gave a new collecting feel that the game had been lacking. The 18 Foils from this set are the only ones that have an extra thick layer of foil that makes the entire card shine more than any other foil set that would be created for the game. This type of foiling cost more for Decipher to make, so they changed the process to be less shinny. <br />
<br />
As Worlds approached, the game continued to not have any new cards. Endor would prove to be the only full set that would be released in 1999. This would be the only year that Decipher seemed to be behind in the creation of the game as the fought for the right to design cards for the new movies as well as the popular novels. During this time, the game seems to float by as all the decks created in June got no change before the Worlds tournament at the end of the year.   <br />
<br />
Once again, Decipher held its Worlds Tournament for SWCCG in November. This time they had their own personal convention known as Deciphercon. It was held in Virginia Beach, which provided players with a great view of the waves as they played their tournament games. Deciphercon was a huge success for Decipher as they provided Shannon Baskin (Mara Jade) and Jeremy Bullock (Boba Fett) to autograph players stuff. The great thing was that all you had to pay was the entry fee into the Con. The autographs were completely free, and there was no limit to how many things you could get signed. Decipher used the Con to advertise their plans for the game. They prepared by having blow ups of the future cards for the game i.e. Mara Jade, The Emperor’s Hand, which would not be released until January of the next year. <br />
<br />
Listed below are the two decks that Gary Carman used to defeat Steven Lewis for the 1999 World Champion Title. As you can see, they are still very different from any year before them. This time, Objectives got the majority of play. DS sported ISB with Outer Rim Scouts, while LS was Hidden Base with Epps and Odds. You can see that the player still must hope to draw all of his locations and characters into hand before he could affectively set up his strategy. The game still has no real way to search for anything short of an ORS with the Abyssin Ornaments and searching for systems with Hidden Base. <br />
  <br />
<br />
<br />
