<br />
<br />
Chapter 5:	Crazy for Reflections<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
With the completion of Endor, Decipher had a new problem to think about. The next set would be Death Star II, which would complete the Trilogy as far as the card game was concerned. At that time, they had not obtained the rights to make the Episode I cards, so Decipher decided to push the release of DSII back. With the extra time gained by pushing back DSII, Decipher released a new line of Enhanced cards to follow the success of the EPPs. Enhanced Cloud City and Enhanced Jabba’s Palace introduced the game to even more versions of popular characters, as well as provide even more permanent weapon characters and permanent pilots in their matching ships. <br />
<br />
Much like the Epps, they were pre-packaged with the same cards in each one with one card showing out. This time though, they would include more than just one card, each ECC and EJP would include 4 unique cards that were the same based on who could be seen on the outside. The ECCs came with 4 packs of Cloud City, while the EJPs had 4 packs of Jabba’s Palace. ECC included such awesome cards as IG-88 with Riot Gun, 4-Lom with Concussion Rifle, Lando with Blaster Pistol, Chewie with Gun, Boba Fett in Slave 1, Lando in Falcon, and two new objectives based around Cloud City. EJP followed the same pattern of ECC by introducing new characters and objectives all based around Jabba’s Palace. The difference in the two was that EJP had fewer permanent weapon characters and more cards that were simply different versions of the main characters. The DS got Mara Jade, The Emperor Hand, Mara Jade’s Lightsaber, Dengar with Blaster Carbine, Jodo Kast, and Zuckess in Mist Hunter, while the LS got Master Luke and Boushh. ECC could be purchased for the first time at Deciphercon 1999, but would not hit stores until mid December. EJP was then released at the beginning of the new year in January 2000. <br />
<br />
To keep the game going as they worked out making future sets past DSII, Decipher created their very popular set Reflections I that was released the same time as EJP. Reflections I gave players a way to purchase a pack of SWCCG and literally obtain cards from all the sets from Premiere to Special Edition. Each pack was crammed with 18 cards, 17 coming at random from anyone one of the for mentioned sets, while the last card was a one of 114 Foils of some of the most popular cards in the game. The Foils were divided up into rarity; Very Rare, Super Rare, and Ultra Rare. Only two cards in the set were Ultra rare, and that meant just that. In a whole case of 10 boxes, there might be one Ultra Rare of either Darth Vader or Luke Skywalker. This made putting a set together an almost impossible task without paying a lot for it. The overwhelming success of the Reflections I set convinced Decipher to produce WAY too much, which is why there are so many to be found to this day on Ebay.<br />
<br />
The new cards gave Decipher a chance to perfect their final set that would conclude the original trilogy. In June, the Third Anthology was released as a last minute product before DSII. The third and final anthology followed the same recipe as the previous two. The player got another long box, this time it was black and covered with stars. The third did however do something different. Since Decipher had no more cards to preview, they simply created 6 unique cards that could only be obtained through the Anthology. The LS got R2 in Red 5, Prisoner 2187, Echo Base Garrison, A New Secret Base, and the MBO objective, while the DS got the SYCFA objective. The released of these cards created a whole new way to set of EBO for LS, as well as give the DS a way to play the Death Star and still go first. <br />
<br />
Finally, as it seemed the set would never come, Death Star II was released in July of 2000. The set completed the original Trilogy with all the locations and characters that were missing from the game. Players could now play with Luke Skywalker, Jedi Knight and Emperor Palaptine, which were the Ultra rare cards in the set and were the first powerful characters to have a 6 destiny number. DSII also introduced a new card type, the Admiral’s Order, which provided additional help too many strategies mainly in space. Players got a big surprise with the set with the introduction of a new starting interrupt; Prepare Defenses DS / Heading For the Medical Frigate LS. This time a player could start the game with 3 Effects as long as they all deployed for free to your side of the table and were always immune to alter. The strength of this starting card is still used currently with anyone playing an Objective.<br />
<br />
Death Star II introduced the game to brand new starter decks that were pre-packed to be instantly playable in a seal deck tournament. The starters included a balance of locations, characters, and starships, which finally made the sealed deck format reliable to a wider range of players. They could be played with a supplement of packs from other sets, this way no one got too much of an advantage from what they pulled. The downside to this product was that it serviced no other purpose other than in sealed deck, so a player would never need to purchase more than one of each with only 1 card being unattainable from other DSII packs; Admiral Piett for DS and Ackbar for LS.       <br />
<br />
DSII was a huge success. The game had finally reached a true high and continued to be the second most popular SSG right under Magic. To prepare the players for Worlds, Decipher released one last product to spice up the decks that had become popular. Jabba’s Palace Sealed Deck hit stores in October 2000. Like the first edition of the Enhanced Sealed Deck format, the JPSDs were composed of 6 collectable boxes all with different pics from characters set in Jabba’s Palace. Each box included 6 packs of Jabba’s Palace and a pre-packed set of 20 cards (10 for each side) that were unique to the JPSD. The most powerful card being No Escape for Darkside because it finally provided a way around Honor of the Jedi, which really hurt DS direct damage during the few months HOTJ existed with no counter.  <br />
<br />
By now you already know what this paragraph is going to be about since we are now up to November 2000. Of course, Worlds at Deciphercon, which was held in Orlando, FL, this year. The turn out was great. This year there was a Wild card where the Top % no matter what would move on to Day 2. With the number of players that showed up to play in the Wild card, the top 45 players out of 167 moved on. Then in Day 2, the top 12 moved on to Day 3. This year was the first year Decipher decided to have complete computer pairings, which meant that a computer could do all the pairings based on the outcome of each game. Wow, that must mean that everything went SO much faster, right?? Well, since all the games had to be keyed into the computer, the pairings took over an hour after each game. So an 8 game tournament that was suppose to be over like at 7, lasted until 2 in the morning. So players that played in Day 1 and 2 had to play 16 games with like 4 hours of sleep, and that is if you went to bed right after the Day 1 tournament was over. No time for playtesting or deck building at this Worlds. If you didn’t have your deck built, you were looking at no sleep for the night. <br />
<br />
As far as product goes, the only thing that was released at the 2000 Worlds was a rare Japanese version of the Hoth 2-Player set that was already rare with so many players needing those Rebel Snowspeeders and Walker Garrisons. They sold out in a few hours and are still one of the rarest product to be had in the SWCCG universe. A new product would not be seen until early in the New Year as Decipher would product more sets in one year than any other year to date. <br />
<br />
Listed below are the two decks that Matt Sokol used to become the 2000 World Champion. You will notice that they are both the exact Objectives that were used to win the 1999 Worlds. So if you didn’t already know, ISB and Hidden Base are the only Back to Back World Champion decks. Of course, they are nothing like the years before or the years after. The point by now is to continue to see the evolution of these Objectives. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
